        understand: "Explain why RuBisCO's oxygenase activity is a significant liability for plant productivity. Your answer must explain what product is formed, what pathway it enters, and what resources are wasted.",
        apply:      "RuBisCO has Km(CO₂) = 10 μM and kcat(carboxylase) = 5 s⁻¹. Atmospheric CO₂ dissolves to approximately 8 μM in the chloroplast stroma. Using the Michaelis-Menten equation, calculate the carboxylation rate as a fraction of Vmax and predict whether increasing atmospheric CO₂ to 16 μM (approximately double current levels) would significantly increase fixation rate.",
        analyze:    "Kinetic data: RuBisCO kcat(CO₂) = 5 s⁻¹, Km(CO₂) = 10 μM; kcat(O₂) = 2 s⁻¹, Km(O₂) = 350 μM. Dissolved concentrations in the stroma: [CO₂] = 8 μM, [O₂] = 250 μM. Calculate the relative rates of carboxylation and oxygenation and analyse the implications for net carbon gain in a C3 plant on a hot, dry day when stomata are partially closed.",
        evaluate:   "Evaluate the claim that RuBisCO's oxygenase activity is merely a design flaw that natural selection has failed to correct. Your evaluation must address: (a) the atmospheric conditions under which RuBisCO evolved; (b) the kinetic trade-offs between CO₂/O₂ specificity and catalytic rate that constrain RuBisCO engineering; (c) why billions of years of selection have not produced an oxygenase-free carboxylase.",
        create:     "Design an experiment using ¹⁴CO₂ pulse-chase labelling to measure the Km of RuBisCO for CO₂ in intact chloroplasts. Specify: (a) how you would vary dissolved CO₂ concentrations without disturbing other Calvin cycle conditions; (b) how you would measure the rate of ¹⁴C incorporation into 3-PGA; (c) how you would plot the data to extract Km; (d) what controls you would include to confirm that RuBisCO — and not another enzyme — is the measured bottleneck."
