        analyze:    "A mutant plant lacks functional RuBisCO activase. In the dark, its Calvin cycle is non-functional (as expected). In the light, Calvin cycle activity is 15% of wild type despite normal ATP and NADPH production. Analyse: (a) why light does not restore full Calvin cycle activity in this mutant; (b) what is happening to RuBisCO active sites in the absence of activase; (c) what effect this would have on the 3-PGA and RuBP pools in the stroma.",
        evaluate:   "Evaluate whether C4 photosynthesis represents a complete solution to the problem of RuBisCO's oxygenase activity. Your evaluation must address: the mechanism by which C4 suppresses photorespiration, the energetic cost of the CO₂-concentrating mechanism, the environmental conditions under which C4 confers a net advantage, and at least one condition where C4 offers no advantage over C3.",
        create:     "Construct a regulatory model of how the Calvin cycle responds to a transition from darkness to full sunlight. Your model must: (a) identify the sequence of molecular events (starting from photon absorption) that activate each regulated Calvin cycle enzyme; (b) specify the time scale of each activation event (seconds vs minutes); (c) predict the order in which the three stages of the Calvin cycle reach full capacity; (d) identify one potential bottleneck during the transition and propose how it could be relieved."
